04459nam a22006255i 9780271088792DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710887927 a10.1515/97802710887922doi  a(DE-B1597)584396  a(OCoLC)1253314170  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aBIO0260002bisacsh1 aLevitt, Laura, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Objects That Remain /cLaura Levitt. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (184 p.) :b10 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDimyonot: Jews and the Cultural Imagination ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPrelude: An Affection for Objects, a Memory of Blood -- tIntroduction: The Afterlife of Objects -- tPart 1 Sacred Texts: The Red Parts -- tChapter 1 The Allure of Bloody Garments A Medieval Interlude -- tChapter 2 In the Poet’s Hand The Red Parts -- tChapter 3 In the Potter’s Hands Containers of Loss -- tPart 2 The Arts and Rites of Holding -- tChapter 4 The Art of Custody Police Property Management -- tChapter 5 The Arts of Conservation and Collections Management -- tChapter 6 Tending to Sacred Objects and Their Afterlives -- tCoda Returning to Atlanta, Carrying On -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOn a November evening in 1989, Laura Levitt was raped in her own bed. Her landlord heard the assault taking place and called 911, but the police arrived too late to apprehend Laura’s attacker. When they left, investigators took items with them—a pair of sweatpants, the bedclothes—and a rape exam was performed at the hospital. However, this evidence was never processed.Decades later, Laura returns to these objects, viewing them not as clues that will lead to the identification of her assailant but rather as a means of engaging traumatic legacies writ large. The Objects That Remain is equal parts personal memoir and fascinating examination of the ways in which the material remains of violent crimes inform our experience of, and thinking about, trauma and loss. Considering artifacts in the United States Holocaust Memorial Museum and evidence in police storage facilities across the country, Laura’s story moves between intimate trauma, the story of an unsolved rape, and genocide. Throughout, she asks what it might mean to do justice to these violent pasts outside the juridical system or through historical empiricism, which are the dominant ways in which we think about evidence from violent crimes and other highly traumatic events.Over the course of her investigation, the author reveals how these objects that remain and the stories that surround them enable forms of intimacy. In this way, she models for us a different kind of reckoning, where justice is an animating process of telling and holding.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311074521440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978027108879240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271088792423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271088792.jpg  a978-3-11-074521-4  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK